<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-05-01T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-05-01T09:00:00-05:00" n="251" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d251">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M)/1888:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-05-01T17:00:00+03:00">May 1, 1941—5
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 2—8:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>379. Personal for Feis. In continuation of my 347, April 27, 9 a.m.
                                If you are interested in making the operation of vessels pay, it
                                looks as if we might supply a couple of cargoes of American citizens
                                from this part of the world if ships would carry passengers and if
                                we had advance notice of return sailings.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>